ewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Abt  , a habitational name from Opatów in Poland."]},{"name":"Apter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Ifor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: (i) relationship name from Old Scandinavian  <i>Ívarr</i>,  <i>Iwar</i>,  <i>Ivar</i> ‘yew-army’. (ii) relationship name, possibly from the Welsh male given name  <i>Ifor</i>; if so, it is not clear that it survives today."],"variants":[{"name":"Ivers","meanings":["Irish: from <b>Ó hÍomhair</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Íomhar</i>’, a Gaelic form of the Old Norse personal name <i>Ívarr</i> (see   Iverson   2), with excrescent English <i>-s</i>. It is occasionally Anglicized as   Howard  . Also a shortened form of <b>Mac Íomhair</b> ‘son of <i>Íomhar</i>’, with excrescent English <i>-s</i>. See   McIver  .","North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Ivar</i> (see   Iversen  ).","English: variant of <b>Iver</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, a habitational name from Iver (Buckinghamshire) named from Old English <i>ȳfre</i> ‘edge or brow of a hill, tip of a promontory’, or from a minor place called with the same word."]},{"name":"Iver","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Iver (Bucks) named from Old English * <i>ȳfre</i> ‘edge or brow of a hill, tip of a promontory’, or from a minor place named with the same word.","2  Scottish: (i) relationship name, reduced form of Irish and Scottish Gaelic  <b>Mac Íomhair</b>,  see  McIvor  . (ii) relationship name from the Old Scandinavian personal name  <i>Ivar</i>;  see  Ivor  ."]},{"name":"Iverson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Iver, Erik, Hjalmer, Lars, Selmer, Thor, Evald, Gunner, Helmer, Ingman, Jarl, Joneen.","Americanized form of Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Iversen   and of Swedish <b>Ivarsson</b> (see   Ivarson  ), all cognates of 2 below.","English (Kent and London): patronymic from Old Norse <i>Ívarr</i>, <i>Iwar</i>, <i>Ivar</i>, a compound of either <i>ív</i> ‘yew tree, bow’ or <i>Ing</i> (the name of a god) + <i>ar</i> ‘warrior’ or ‘spear’. Alternatively, the name might be a patronymic from the Welsh male personal name <i>Ifor</i>, itself from British Celtic <i>Iūdomāros</i> ‘lord’ + ‘great’, but if so, it is not clear that it survives today."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Cuhelyn Ap Ifor Lord of Builth was born in 0907, in Powys, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Ifor Seferios Gilman, was 25 and his mother, Mrs. Seferios Gilman, was 22. He married Rhiengar Gwen ferch Grono of Denbighshire in 0990, in Radnorshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"0907–":"0907–Surnud","0907–Male":"0907–Surnud","0915–Female":"0915–Surnud","0950–1010":"0950–1010","0882–0940":"0882–0940","0885–0950":"0885–0950","990":"0990","0 ___ 0899":"5. jaanuar 0899 kuni 4. jaanuar 0900","0950":"0950","0885":"0885","0940":"0940","0882":"0882","0907":"0907","1010":"1010","about 0950":"umbes 0950","0915":"0915","Radnorshire, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales","Powys, Wales":"Powys, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"0907–":"0907–Kuollut","0907–Male":"0907–Kuollut","0915–Female":"0915–Kuollut","0950–1010":"0950–1010","0882–0940":"0882–0940","0885–0950":"0885–0950","990":"0990","0 ___ 0899":"vuodesta 5. tammikuuta 0899 vuoteen 4. tammikuuta 0900","0950":"0950","0885":"0885","0940":"0940","0882":"0882","0907":"0907","1010":"1010","about 0950":"noin 0950","0915":"0915","Radnorshire, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales","Powys, Wales":"Powys, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"0907–":"0907–Décédé","0907–Male":"0907–Décédé","0915–Female":"0915–Décédée","0950–1010":"0950–1010","0882–0940":"0882